// bigint.su — arbitrary-precision integer arithmetic helpers.
//
// Per planning/sutra-spec/arbitrary-precision.md (Option A, all four
// sub-decisions locked Emma 2026-05-28). Ergonomic wrappers over the
// substrate intrinsics int_div, int_mod, and digit_array_add (declared
// in logic.su § "Section 3 — intrinsic declarations").
//
// Representation: a BigInt value is a 1-d substrate vector of `max_digits`
// elements, each holding a base-10 digit in [0, 9]. Little-endian:
// digit[0] is the ones place, digit[1] is the tens, ..., digit[N-1] is
// the most-significant place. Overflow saturates by dropping the top
// carry-out (matching the String overflow posture per strings.md).
//
// The wider `BigInt<MAX>` class form (sub-decision 1) is deferred to a
// follow-on commit; v1 ships these functions so that callers can do
// arbitrary-precision arithmetic before the class wrapper lands.
//
// Worked example end-to-end: experiments/bigint_worked_example.py
// demonstrates `bigint_add` on the spec's `"99999" + "1" = "100000"`
// case + 8 other cases including cascade and overflow-saturates.


// bigint_add — add two digit-array BigInt values.
//
// Inputs: 1-d vectors `a` and `b` of equal length N, each digit in
// [0, 10). Returns: 1-d vector of length N with the carry-propagated
// sum digits; the top-digit carry-out is silently dropped (overflow
// saturates at N digits). Substrate-pure end-to-end — the digit array
// never round-trips through host scalars; carry propagation is the
// `digit_array_add` substrate intrinsic.
function vector bigint_add(vector a, vector b) {
    return digit_array_add(a, b, 10);
}
